%META:TOPICPARENT{name="WebHome"}%
---+ Energy Thresholds

%TOC%

The right-side panel carries one slider tab per object class. A cell,
cluster or track is drawn only when its energy (or =p_{T}=) falls inside
the tab's =[min, max]= window. The sliders do not modify the
underlying event &mdash; they are display-time filters. Switching
events preserves your threshold settings; toggling a sub-detector off
via the [[UserInterface#Detector_Layers_panel][Layers panel]] overrides
its threshold (hidden = hidden).

<img src="images/threshold-panel.png" alt="Threshold panel open over the canvas (full-screen context)" style="width:100%;max-width:900px;height:auto;display:block;" />

---++ Tabs

| *Tab*     | *Object*              | *Units* | *Default floor* | *Default ceiling*    |
| TILE      | TileCal cell          | GeV     | 0               | auto (P97 of event)  |
| LAr       | LAr EMB / EMEC cell   | GeV     | 0               | auto (P97)           |
| FCAL      | LAr FCAL cell         | GeV     | 0               | auto (P97)           |
| HEC       | LAr HEC cell          | GeV     | 0               | auto (P97)           |
| Track     | Reconstructed track   | GeV     | 0.5             | &mdash;              |
| Cluster   | Topological cluster   | GeV     | 0.5             | &mdash;              |

The _Cluster_ tab exposes an extra =Cluster Threshold= on/off switch
(=Shift+K=): when off, all clusters render regardless of =E_{T}=
&mdash; useful when inspecting sub-GeV activity around a jet.

---++ P97 auto-scaling

By default the ceiling of every calorimeter tab is set to the 97th
percentile of that sub-detector's cell energies in the current event.
The palette therefore spans the bulk of the deposits rather than being
compressed by a single high-energy outlier.

The read-out above each slider shows the current ceiling (e.g.
=2.00 GeV=). Double-click the slider to re-sample P97 if the event has
just changed; type a numeric value in the text input to lock an
absolute ceiling that survives event switches (useful when comparing
two captures side-by-side).

---++ Typed input

Every tab exposes a text field below the slider. Accepted formats:

<verbatim>
200            -> 200 MeV  (default unit)
200 MeV        -> 200 MeV
1.5 GeV        -> 1 500 MeV
2e3            -> 2 000 MeV
0.1 TeV        -> 100 GeV
</verbatim>

Invalid input is silently ignored and the slider stays put; no error
dialog interrupts the rendering loop.

---++ Palette behaviour

Each sub-detector has a per-tab cold-to-hot gradient (see
[[Overview][Overview]] for the accent colours). Within =[min, max]=:

   * A hit at =min= renders with the coldest colour of the sub-detector palette.
   * A hit at =max= renders with the hottest colour.
   * Hits below =min= are culled from the scene.
   * Hits above =max= saturate at the hottest colour (clipping).

---++ Interaction with _All cells_

When the [[UserInterface#Show_all_cells][All cells]] toggle (=V=) is
on, the threshold floor is bypassed for visibility: every cell of an
enabled sub-detector is drawn, painting zero-energy cells with the
coldest palette colour. The _max_ ceiling still scales the palette
gradient for cells that _do_ carry a hit, so a low threshold ceiling
still brightens mid-energy activity against the geometry backdrop.

Turning _All cells_ off restores the strict =E &ge; min= visibility
rule.

---++ Recipes

| *Goal*                                   | *Action*                                           |
| Hide sub-MIP noise                       | Raise TILE / LAr floor to a few hundred MeV        |
| Show only the shower core                | Raise floors on TILE and LAr simultaneously        |
| Keep the scale fixed across events       | Lock each ceiling with a typed value               |
| Isolate a single high-=p_{T}= track      | Raise _Track_ floor to the desired =p_{T}=         |
| Compare two events in the same capture   | Same typed ceilings on both captures               |
| Reveal the geometry of an empty corner   | Toggle _All cells_ (=V=), then scan with the orbit |

---++ Interaction with geometry

Thresholds never hide the geometry mesh itself &mdash; they hide the
_energy colouring_ on cells that fail the filter. To remove a whole
sub-detector from the scene, use the
[[UserInterface#Detector_Layers_panel][Detector Layers panel]]. To
carve a volume (independent of thresholds) use the
[[UserInterface#Slicer_cylindrical_wedge][Slicer]].

